<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-03-04T07:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-03-04T07:00:00-05:00" n="102" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d102">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">811.20 Defense (M) Portugal/1442:
                                Telegram</note>
                            <head>
                                <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Portugal</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Norweb</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                                </hi>
                            </head>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right">
                                    <placeName>
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Lisbon</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-03-04T12:00:00+00:00">March
                                        4, 1944—noon</date>.<lb/>[Received 7:12 p.m.]</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>683. The British Ambassador saw the Secretary General of Foreign
                                Office yesterday in the matter of the temporary embargo on wolfram
                                exports to Germany. According to Campbell while Sampaio was not of
                                course in a position to commit the Portuguese Government to anything
                                he was impressed though worried. Sampaio indicated that Salazar had
                                summoned for a meeting the chief officials concerned with this
                                question.</p>
                            <p>I shall follow up this <hi rend="italic">démarche</hi> at the
                                beginning of next week by which time the matter should have been
                                given full consideration by the Portuguese Government.</p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Norweb</hi>
                                </signed>
                            </closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>